#!/bin/sh
#
# Installs development environment for Claude Code for current user.
#
# Note that the Claude Code application is installed locally and specifically
# for current user only!
#
# Includes additional dependencies and configuration for running sandboxed
# mode, and with curated initial configuration for privacy and minimized
# unnecessary network traffic. Also improves XDG Base Directory conformance
# by configuring Claude to use ~/.config/claude rather than cluttering the
# home directory root with ~/.claude and ~/.claude.json.
#
# Note that the sandboxed mode requires two (otherwise optional) dependencies
# socat and bubblewrap. If these are not installed, this script will just
# report a warning, and Claude will automatically disable sandboxing until
# they are installed.
#
# This is a variant which creates a bit more standalone setup than the regular
# setup created by for instance the official installation script
# https://claude.ai/install.sh. Possible advantages are a more stable setup,
# and more minimal disk usage and network traffic. It does not rely on the
# official Claude Code bootstrapper command 'claude install', but instead
# simply downloads the application executable directly as ~/.local/bin/claude.
# The main difference is there will only ever be a single executable installed.
# With a regular install there are multiple versions of the executable
# installed into directory ~/.local/share/claude/versions, and
# ~/.local/bin/claude is just a symlink to the current (latest) version. The
# application executable is quite big, over 200 MiB. So the regular setup
# wastes disk space. Also the install process wastes network traffic, because
# the executable is actually downloaded twice (first time only to get a
# temporary copy to run the install command with).
#
# Note that if the built-in update functionality is used, either the
# auto-updater or the 'claude update' command, it will migrate to the regular
# setup! So to keep this "standalone" setup, update must be done manually by
# downloading and replacing the binary. The utility script
# arch-dev-claude-standalone-upgrade will do that! To migrate back to
# standalone setup when default paths are used, the following command should
# work:
#   mv "$(readlink ~/.local/bin/claude)" ~/.local/bin/claude && rm -rf ~/.local/share/claude/versions
#
# The official installation method is by running a bootstrapper script
# https://claude.ai/install.sh. This is a small utility script that downloads
# the application executable as a temporary file, verifies published checksums,
# executes it with argument "install", and then deletes it again. The script is
# very small, and handles different Linux-based platforms and distros, so as an
# alternative one can easily skip the intermediate script and do the specific
# steps necessary for Arch Linux distribution and x64 platform directly. The
# main steps for performing a regular installation this way are:
# - Fetch the specific version number for the latest version.
# - Download the version manifest and extract checksum (and size) for the
#   application executable.
# - Download the application executable as a temporary file, and verify
#   checksum (and size).
# - Run the downloaded application executable with argument "install", to
#   perform the built-in installation procedure. This installs the executable
#   into ~/.local/share/claude/versions, creates symlink ~/.local/bin/claude,
#   and creates directory structure in home (~/.claude.json, ~/.claude/,
#   ~/.cache/, ~/.local/ etc). Without arguments, this installs the latest
#   version, but can also specify "latest", "stable" or a specific version.
#   Note that this actually downloads the application executable it installs,
#   and when this is the latest version it is exactly the same as the one we
#   have already downloaded and are running the install with! That is 200 MiB
#   wasted download!
# Skipping the install procedure like we do here works just fine. In addition
# to the lack of a versioned symbolic link described previously, it does not
# create the initial home directory structure either, but this will be created
# when the application is started for the first time anyway.
#
# This downloads the specified or latest version of the application executable
# into the user-specific local install location, making it available as path
# ~/.local/bin/claude. It also ensures ~/.local/bin is added to PATH in
# ~/.bashrc for future shell sessions. Then it creates a curated initial
# configuration in current user's Claude configuration file (settings.json).
# First of all this disables the built-in auto-updater, which is necessary to
# keep the standalone setup! It also enables the sandbox mode with regular
# permissions (not auto-allow) by default, disables all MCP servers so that
# user later must explicitly allow any to be used, and disables automatic
# addition of the official plugin marketplace on first run so that user can
# decide later if it should be added manually. Also, it disables telemetry,
# error reporting, feedback prompts and dynamic updating of terminal title
# based on conversation context. Finally, it ensures CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is
# set in ~/.bashrc pointing to the XDG-based configuration directory
# $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/claude, or ~/.config/claude if not set. This makes the
# Claude setup more aligned with the XDG Base Directory Specification: not
# only is the configuration directory placed under ~/.config rather than the
# home root, but the global configuration file ~/.claude.json is also
# relocated into that same directory instead of cluttering the home root.
# Note that the result is still not entirely XDG conformant, as the config
# directory contains a lot more than strictly configuration, and should have
# been more splitted across the other XDG directories (data, state, cache).
# By the way, Claude does use these other XDG directories already for some
# things, and considers corresponding variables (XDG_DATA_HOME, XDG_STATE_HOME,
# XDG_CACHE_HOME), as well as using the XDG conventional location for the
# executable file. This also means that even though we override
# CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR, Claude still puts files in other locations.
#
# If the system has not been recently upgraded, which is done automatically
# during setup by the arch-setup (arch-setup-packages) script, to ensure you
# install the latest versions of the packages you should run the arch-upgrade
# script first.
#
# This script does not refresh package database and upgrade existing packages.
# If we were to do it, we would have to be careful not end up in a state of
# partial upgrades (remember to either do both --refresh (-y) and
# --sysupgrade (-u), or none of them, at least never just --refresh (-y)), and
# then there is also the potential issue with signing keys. These are exactly
# things that the arch-upgrade script is handling.
#
# Supports optional argument --version <version>/--version=<version> to install
# a specific version instead of the latest. The version can be specified as
# the name of a release channel, "latest" (latest published version) or
# "stable" (one week delayed versions, skipping versions with major
# regressions), or as a version number. When not specified, defaults to
# "latest".
#
# NOTE: Assumes basic tools are already installed, including sudo.
# Run script ./arch-setup first to ensure this!
#
# SEE ALSO:
#   https://storage.googleapis.com/claude-code-dist-86c565f3-f756-42ad-8dfa-d59b1c096819/claude-code-releases/bootstrap.sh
#

# If we could always assume that the distro is always set up with a non-root
# default user, then we could verify we are not running as root, since this
# considers a local Claude Code installation for the current user only!
#if [ ${EUID:-$(id -u)} -eq 0 ]; then
#    echo 'Please do not run this script as root' >&2
#    exit 1
#fi

# Parse arguments.
version=latest
while [ $# -gt 0 ]; do
    case "$1" in
        --version)
            shift
            version="$1"
            ;;
        --version=*)
            version="${1#--version=}"
            ;;
        *)
            echo "Unknown argument: $1" >&2
            exit 1
            ;;
    esac
    shift
done

# Resolve XDG conventional user binary directory.
# This is where the Claude executable is installed by default, and here we
# assume it was not manually installed elsewhere.
bin_dir="${HOME}/.local/bin"
bin_dir_expr='${HOME}/.local/bin'

if [ -f "${bin_dir}/claude" ]; then
    echo "There is an existing file '${bin_dir}/claude' so Claude Code is probably already installed!" >&2
    exit 1
fi

if command -v claude > /dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "There is an existing command 'claude' so Claude Code is probably already installed!" >&2
    exit 1
fi

# We do configure sandbox mode below, but it will simply be ignored if not
# dependencies are installed.
# Currently we just check for them, to keep the install script user-specific,
# and avoid requiring sudo.
if ! pacman -Qi socat bubblewrap > /dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "WARNING: Missing dependencies socat or bubblewrap required for sandboxed mode"
fi
#OLD:
#echo "Making sure optional dependencies socat and bubblewrap are installed..."
#if ! sudo pacman --sync --needed "$@" socat bubblewrap; then
#    echo "Failed!" >&2
#    exit 1
#fi

#echo
echo "Installing Claude Code..."

# Download version and install as user-specific application ~/.local/bin/claude.
# For atomic binary replacement, downloads into temporary location, before moving into place.
base_url=https://storage.googleapis.com/claude-code-dist-86c565f3-f756-42ad-8dfa-d59b1c096819/claude-code-releases
if echo "$version" | grep -qE '^[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+$'; then
    echo "Specific version ${version}"
else
    echo "Release channel '${version}'"
    version=$(curl --fail --silent --show-error --location "${base_url}/${version}")
    if [ -z "$version" ]; then
        echo "Failed to resolve release channel version" >&2
        exit 1
    fi
    echo "Version ${version}"
fi
manifest=$(curl --fail --silent --show-error --location "${base_url}/${version}/manifest.json" | tr -d '\n\r\t' | sed 's/ \+/ /g')
if [ -z "$manifest" ]; then
    echo "Failed to fetch version manifest" >&2
    exit 1
fi
manifest_version=$(echo "$manifest" | sed 's/.*"version": "\([^"]*\)".*/\1/')
if [ "$version" != "$manifest_version" ]; then
    echo "Version mismatch, expected ${version} but was ${manifest_version}" >&2
    exit 1
fi
manifest_date=$(echo "$manifest" | sed 's/.*"buildDate": "\([^"]*\)".*/\1/')
if [ -n "$manifest_date" ]; then
    echo "It was published $(date --date="${manifest_date}" 2> /dev/null) (${manifest_date})"
else
    echo "Unable to find its published date"
fi
expected_size=$(echo "$manifest" | sed 's/.*"linux-x64": {[^}]*"size": \([0-9]*\).*/\1/')
if [ -z "$expected_size" ]; then
    echo "Failed to fetch expected size from version manifest" >&2
    exit 1
fi
expected_checksum=$(echo "$manifest" | sed 's/.*"linux-x64": {[^}]*"checksum": "\([^"]*\)".*/\1/')
if [ -z "$expected_checksum" ]; then
    echo "Failed to fetch expected checksum from version manifest" >&2
    exit 1
fi
echo "Downloading..."
if ! curl --fail --silent --show-error --location "${base_url}/${version}/linux-x64/claude" --output "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}"; then
    echo "Failed!" >&2
    exit 1
fi
echo "Verifying..."
actual_size=$(stat -c %s "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}")
if [ "$actual_size" != "$expected_size" ]; then
    echo "Size mismatch, expected ${expected_size} but was ${actual_size}" >&2
    rm --force "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}"
    exit 1
fi
actual_checksum=$(sha256sum "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}" | cut -d' ' -f1)
if [ "$actual_checksum" != "$expected_checksum" ]; then
    echo "Checksum mismatch, expected ${expected_checksum} but was ${actual_checksum}" >&2
    rm --force "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}"
    exit 1
fi
echo "Installing..."
if ! mkdir -p "${bin_dir}"; then
    echo "Failed to create directory '${bin_dir}'" >&2
    rm --force "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}"
    exit 1
fi
if ! mv "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}" "${bin_dir}/claude"; then
    echo "Failed to install new executable as '${bin_dir}/claude'" >&2
    rm --force "/tmp/claude-installer-${version}"
    exit 1
fi
chmod +x "${bin_dir}/claude"
echo "Executable 'claude' is now installed in location '${bin_dir}'"
echo "Checking it by running '${bin_dir}/claude --version'..."
echo -n "Claude version output: "
"${bin_dir}/claude" --version || echo "error (exit code $?)"

# Ensure the Claude executable is in PATH in future shell sessions.
# It is installed into ~/.local/bin, which is a commonly used directory for
# user-specific executables, but on Arch Linux it is not in PATH by default.
# NOTE: Adding the PATH variable into the user profile '.bashrc'. One may
# prefer '.bash_profile' for such things, but assuming Arch Linux default setup
# where '.bash_profile' sources '.bashrc' everything might just as well be
# put into '.bashrc'. Default '.bashrc' has a test for if the shell is running
# interactively, so to make the PATH changes apply even when not running
# interactively, like it would if put into '.bash_profile', then it needs to
# be above this test. That is not ensured automatically here, but just noted
# in a message for user to do manually. Also, since this is in bash-specific
# profile, it will not have effect when running POSIX/sh type shell.
# NOTE: Accurately detecting if this is already permanently configured in the
# user profile in any possible way is complex, so the checks are simply looking
# at the PATH in the current session. This may misbehave, e.g. if claude was
# uninstalled and setting of PATH in profile was removed in the current shell
# session and then running this to reinstall, it will find the executable in
# PATH while in future sessions it will no longer be.
if echo ":${PATH}:" | grep --quiet --fixed-strings ":${bin_dir}:"; then
    echo "The location is already in the PATH variable of this shell session"
    if claude_command=$(command -v claude); then
        if [ "$claude_command" != "${bin_dir}/claude" ]; then
            echo "WARNING: Command 'claude' in this shell session resolves to a different path."
            echo "  Expected path was '${bin_dir}/claude'"
            echo "  Path in this session is '${claude_command}'"
            echo "Checking the command in this session by running 'claude --version'..."
            echo -n "Claude version output: "
            claude --version || echo "error (exit code $?)"
            echo "WARNING: Something is wrong with the installation or environment"
        else
            # Note: Do not indicate claude can be used immediately, due to the
            # CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR logic below may require restarting the session!
            #echo "Command 'claude' can be used in this shell session"
            echo "NOTICE: Assuming PATH is persisted in the profile so the same will be true also"
            echo "  for future sessions. If this is not the case, you can manually fix it by"
            echo "  adding something like the following into the user profile '.bashrc',"
            echo "  preferably near the top, before any check for shell running interactively:"
            echo '  [[ ":$PATH:" != *":'"${bin_dir_expr}"':"* ]] && PATH="${PATH:+$PATH:}'"${bin_dir_expr}"'"'
        fi
    else
        echo "WARNING: Command 'claude' is not available in this shell session"
        echo "WARNING: Something is wrong with the installation or environment"
    fi
else
    echo "The location is not in the PATH variable of this shell session"
    if [ ! -f "${HOME}/.bashrc" ]; then
        echo "WARNING: User profile '.bashrc' does not exist"
        echo "WARNING: Unable to add the location to PATH automatically. You can fix this"
        echo "  manually by adding something like this, preferably near the top, before any"
        echo "  check for shell running interactively"
        echo '[[ ":$PATH:" != *":'"${bin_dir_expr}"':"* ]] && PATH="${PATH:+$PATH:}'"${bin_dir_expr}"'"'
    else
        echo "Adding the location to PATH in user profile '.bashrc'"
        echo "NOTICE: This will be added to the end of the file, but if the file has a check"
        echo "  for shell running interactively you might consider moving it above that check."
        echo "  If this has recently already been configured in your profile but without"
        echo "  restarting the shell, the result will be a duplicate entry."
        echo '[[ ":$PATH:" != *":'"${bin_dir_expr}"':"* ]] && PATH="${PATH:+$PATH:}'"${bin_dir_expr}"'"' >> "${HOME}/.bashrc"
        echo "NOTICE: You still cannot run command 'claude' without path in this shell session"
        #echo "NOTICE: This takes effect in new shell sessions only"
    fi
fi

#echo
echo "Configuring Claude Code..."

# Resolve Claude-specific configuration directory.
# When CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is not already set, default to the XDG config home
# location: $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/claude if set, otherwise ~/.config/claude.
# Claude does not natively consider XDG_CONFIG_HOME, so this script also
# ensures CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is set in the shell profile so Claude uses this
# location in all future sessions. Setting CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR not only moves
# the configuration directory from ~/.claude to the given location, but also
# relocates the global configuration file ~/.claude.json from the home
# directory root into that same directory (as .claude.json within it). This
# makes the Claude setup fully aligned with the XDG Base Directory
# Specification.
config_dir="${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR:-${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/claude}" # The actual expanded value
if [ -n "${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}" ]; then
    config_dir_expr="${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}" # Dummy, just use the literal value
    echo "Variable CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is currently defined"
    echo "Using configuration directory '${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}' given by CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR"
else
    config_dir_expr='${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/claude' # The exact unexpanded expression to use in .bashrc
    if [ -n "${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}" ]; then
        echo "Variable CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is currently not defined but XDG_CONFIG_HOME is"
        echo "Using configuration directory '${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/claude' based on XDG_CONFIG_HOME"
        # If we wanted the more specific expression without fallback to $HOME in .bashrc:
        #   config_dir_expr='${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/claude'
        #echo "Using configuration directory '${XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/claude' based on XDG_CONFIG_HOME"
    else
        echo "Variables CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR and XDG_CONFIG_HOME are not currently defined"
        echo "Using configuration directory '${HOME}/.config/claude' from script defaults"
        # If we wanted the more specific expression without considering $XDG_CONFIG_HOME in .bashrc:
        #   config_dir_expr='${HOME}/.config/claude'
        #echo "Using configuration directory '${HOME}/.config/claude' from script defaults"
    fi
fi

# Write relevant settings to the Claude configuration file (${config_dir}/settings.json,
# by default in this script ~/.config/claude/settings.json, while the regular
# Claude default is ~/.claude/settings.json):
# - Enable sandbox, but with regular permissions mode (auto-allow is default).
#   This will be ignored if not both of the (otherwise optional) dependencies
#   socat and bubblewrap are installed.
# - Disable all MCP servers.
# - Disable auto-updater. Important to avoid the standalone setup being
#   migrated to a regular setup! The application must be updated by downloading
#   the new version manually, cannot use the 'claude update' command either.
#   By default Claude checks for updates on startup and periodically while
#   running, and it will download and install in the background, and they take
#   effect the next time Claude Code is started.
#   - DISABLE_AUTOUPDATER=1
# - Skip automatic addition of the official plugin marketplace on first run.
#   - CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_OFFICIAL_MARKETPLACE_AUTOINSTALL=1
#   - It can be done manually later, from the /plugin slash command, by adding
#     "anthropics/claude-plugins-official" as a Marketplace.
# - Enable more privacy, minimize interference and unnecessary network traffic.
#   - Disable telemetry, error reporting and feedback prompts.
#     - DISABLE_TELEMETRY=1
#       - Opt out of Statsig telemetry.
#       - This implicitly also sets CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY=1.
#     - DISABLE_FEEDBACK_COMMAND=1
#       - Disables the /feedback command.
#     - DISABLE_ERROR_REPORTING=1
#       - Opt out of Sentry error reporting.
#     - CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY=1
#       - Disable the "How is Claude doing?" session quality surveys.
#       - This is already implicitly disabled due to DISABLE_TELEMETRY=1, but we
#         set it anyway for completeness, and just in case.
#   - Disable automatic terminal title updates based on conversation context.
#     - CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_TERMINAL_TITLE=1
#   - Disable everything leading to unnecessary network traffic, which implicitly
#     includes all of the above.
#     - CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC=1
#       - Equivalent of setting DISABLE_AUTOUPDATER, DISABLE_FEEDBACK_COMMAND,
#         DISABLE_ERROR_REPORTING, and DISABLE_TELEMETRY. Also since
#         CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY is implicit when DISABLE_TELEMETRY,
#         setting CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC will in reality
#         cover all of the environment variables above! We could therefore remove
#         all others, but we set them anyway for completeness, and just in case.
#         Also, should we later decide to keep the auto-updater enabled, we can
#         no longer use CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC, and would
#         then have to reintroduce all others.
settings_file="${config_dir}/settings.json"
if [ ! -f "$settings_file" ] || [ -w "$settings_file" ]; then
    current=$([ -s "$settings_file" ] && cat "$settings_file")
    if [ -z "$current" ] || [ "$current" = "{}" ]; then
        echo "Creating initial user settings as new file 'settings.json'"
        mkdir -p "$(dirname "$settings_file")"
        cat > "$settings_file" << 'EOF'
{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json",
  "sandbox": {
    "enabled": true,
    "autoAllowBashIfSandboxed": false
  },
  "allowedMcpServers": [],
  "env": {
    "DISABLE_TELEMETRY": "1",
    "DISABLE_FEEDBACK_COMMAND": "1",
    "DISABLE_ERROR_REPORTING": "1",
    "DISABLE_AUTOUPDATER": "1",
    "CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_FEEDBACK_SURVEY": "1",
    "CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC": "1",
    "CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_OFFICIAL_MARKETPLACE_AUTOINSTALL": "1",
    "CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_TERMINAL_TITLE": "1"
  }
}
EOF
    else
        echo "Keeping existing user settings in file 'settings.json'"
        echo "NOTICE: Make sure the settings are correct and valid for the standalone setup."
        echo "  Check especially that DISABLE_AUTOUPDATER=1 is set."
    fi
else
    echo "WARNING: Skipping initial user settings because there is an existing file"
    echo "  'settings.json' which is not writable."
fi

# Ensure Claude uses the configured configuration directory in future sessions.
# Claude does not natively consider XDG_CONFIG_HOME, so it would otherwise
# fall back to its built-in default directory ~/.claude for configuration
# files and keep the global configuration file ~/.claude.json in the home
# directory root, ignoring the configuration written to the configured location
# above. By exporting CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR in the shell profile, we both direct
# Claude to the correct configuration directory and cause it to store
# .claude.json within that directory rather than at the home directory root.
# If CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is already set in the current session but not yet in the
# shell profile, it will still be added and a warning is issued.
# NOTE: As when updating PATH above, we set this in .bashrc.
if [ ! -f "${HOME}/.bashrc" ]; then
    echo "WARNING: User profile '.bashrc' does not exist"
    echo "WARNING: Unable to override configuration directory with CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR"
    echo "  automatically. You need to make sure the following are executed before"
    echo "  starting claude:"
    echo "  export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=\"${config_dir_expr}\""
elif grep --quiet --extended-regexp '^export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=' "${HOME}/.bashrc"; then
    existing_expr=$(sed -n 's/^export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR="\(.*\)"$/\1/p' "${HOME}/.bashrc" | tail -1)
    eval "existing_path=\"$existing_expr\""
    if [ "$existing_path" = "$config_dir" ]; then # Note: This compare fully expanded paths, so may in fact use different variable references etc.
        echo "The user profile '.bashrc' already sets the configuration directory with CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR"
        if [ -z "${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}" ]; then
            echo "NOTICE: Variable CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is not in the current shell session"
            echo "WARNING: Restart the shell session or run the following before starting claude:"
            echo "  export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=\"${config_dir_expr}\""
        fi
    else
        echo "WARNING: Configuration directory (CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR) in '.bashrc' resolves to"
        echo "  '${existing_expr}' but expected '${config_dir_expr}'"
    fi
else
    echo "Overriding configuration directory with CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR in user profile '.bashrc'"
    echo "NOTICE: This will be added to the end of the file, but if the file has a check"
    echo "  for shell running interactively you might consider moving it above that check."
    echo "export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=\"${config_dir_expr}\"" >> "${HOME}/.bashrc"
    if [ -n "${CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR}" ]; then
        # It is implied that the value of $CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is the same as
        # $config_dir at this point, due to the logic where we set config_dir.
        echo "Since the variable CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR is already set in the current shell session"
        echo "  it should be safe to start claude immediately, but you may have to restart the"
        echo "  shell session for any PATH changes reported above to take effect."
    else
        echo "WARNING: Restart the shell session or run the following before starting claude:"
        echo "  export CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR=\"${config_dir_expr}\""
    fi
fi
